Patient: What should I know about fluid intake with heart failure?

Healthcare Educator: It's important to limit your daily fluid intake to prevent fluid buildup in your body.

Patient: How much fluid should I drink?

Healthcare Educator: Try to limit your intake to 6 to 9 cups of fluids a day.

Patient: Does this include all types of fluids?

Healthcare Educator: Yes, this includes water, juice, milk, tea, coffee, and even soup.

Patient: What happens if I drink too much fluid?

Healthcare Educator: Too much fluid can cause swelling, weight gain, and make your heart work harder.

Patient: What if I feel thirsty?

Healthcare Educator: If you're thirsty, try rinsing your mouth or sucking on ice chips or a lemon slice.

Patient: Can I drink alcohol?

Healthcare Educator: It's best to avoid alcohol. It can weaken your heart and interact with your medications.

Patient: Do I need to measure my fluid intake?

Healthcare Educator: Yes, it's a good idea to measure your fluids to stay within your limit.

Patient: What about when it's hot and I sweat a lot?

Healthcare Educator: If you're sweating more, you may need more fluid. But, remember to stay within your limit.

Patient: Can I drink more if I exercise?

Healthcare Educator: Yes, but don't exceed your daily limit. Replace fluid slowly after exercise.

Patient: What about during meals?

Healthcare Educator: Try to drink most of your fluids between meals. This can also help control your appetite.

Patient: Will this fluid restriction help my heart?

Healthcare Educator: Absolutely! It will help your heart not to work as hard and reduce your symptoms.

Patient: What should I do if I accidentally exceed my limit?

Healthcare Educator: Don't panic. Just go back to your limit the next day and monitor your weight.